{
  "texts": [
    "To be precise, the authors study two settings of choice modelling-feature-free and featurebased-and propose neural network models that are able to capture both, the intrinsic utility for each candidate choice and the effect that the assortment has on the choice probability.",
    "The authors provide evidence that the proposed deep learningbased choice models are capable of recovering existing choice models with an effective learning procedure.",
    "Moreover, they find that such models are particularly useful in case the underlying model/training data are too complex to be described by a simpler choice model such as MNL and when there are sufficient training data (e.g.",
    "5000 samples for 20-50 products).",
    "Following this, Wang et al. (2023a) propose a mixed-integer programming formulation for the corresponding assortment problem that is solvable by off-the-shelf integer programming solvers."
  ]
}